This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.

Summary:
1. Primary Request and Intent:

This is an ongoing `/openspec-apply-change outline-edit-enforcement` implementation session (OpenSpec spec-driven workflow) for an Obsidian plugin ("True Outliner") that maps markdown documents to an outline tree and enforces structural editing semantics. The session has proceeded through the full 21-task implementation plus FIVE rounds of real-vault manual-pass feedback from the user, each following a strict "docs first, then implementation, then status report" workflow the user explicitly established:

- Round 1 (initial): Implement all 21 tasks from `tasks.md` (pure ops, verdict layer, funnel wiring, e2e suite, verification) — completed, but real-vault manual pass (5.2) explicitly requires the user's own hands/judgment (subjective feel), which I flagged as blocking.
- Round 2 (first manual pass): User reported bugs from actually using the plugin — spawned the "chrome-transparency" principle (gap lines/markers are storage chrome; edit semantics must not depend on them) and required implementing D9-D11 amendments (merge table rewrite, split-with-children fix, cursor-derived merge recognition).
- Round 3 (second manual pass): User reported a merge cursor bug (D12) and asked for my "honest take" on whether cursor NAVIGATION (not just edits) should also respect chrome-transparency. User explicitly said: "before you jump into the implementation, make sure that the SDD documentation is updated and record the ideas for the follow up work somewhere as well... docs first, then implementation of what we agreed on here, then the status on the completion of the change." User agreed to land marker-transparency now (D13) and defer gap-line cursor navigation to a future change combined with selection-UX work.
- Round 4 (third manual pass): User reported paste bugs (single-node-with-children never re-indexed — D15) and a redo-cursor bug and a delete→undo→redo-cursor-on-chrome bug. I fixed D15, could not reproduce the redo bugs despite 5+ e2e attempts, and asked for more specific repro info, explicitly documenting: "Recorded rather than silently dropped... more specific repro steps requested from the user."
- Round 5 (fourth/fifth manual pass, MOST RECENT): User reported the D15 fix was incomplete ("the re-indentation math must be still partially broken... at the +2 depth or more, it resets back to the original") and gave an EXACT, precise redo-cursor repro:
  ```
  paragraph A

  paragraph B
  ```
  "1. cursor at the start of paragraph B. 2. press backspace. paragraphs merged, cursor between the merged paragraphs (after `A`). 3. undo (cmd-Z), initial state. cursor at the start of paragraph B, same as at the start. 4. redo (cmd-shift-Z), same merge. but the cursor is on the next (gap) line. this is the problem! nothing else happening between the steps. macOS, desktop Obsidian, using keyboard."

  The user's explicit instructions for this round were: "try to figure out why the testing harness is not detecting this behavior. and try to figure the reason for this behavior from the current implementation, even if you can't reproduce it. if you need any more debug information I can provide through manual testing, let's do it." — and separately: "for the paste bug, see `Paste bug repro` in the test-vault. let me know if that is enough to understand the problematic behavior."

The overarching intent throughout: implement `outline-edit-enforcement` (Phase C of a multi-phase outline-mode enforcement system) correctly, validate rigorously via automated tests AND real-vault manual passes, treat the user's manual-pass findings as authoritative bug reports to root-cause (not just patch symptomatically), keep OpenSpec SDD documentation (design.md, specs, tasks.md) and `docs/research/` findings synchronized with every code change, and be transparent when something cannot be reproduced rather than guessing/pretending to fix it.

2. Key Technical Concepts:
   - OpenSpec spec-driven development workflow (proposal/design/specs/tasks artifacts, delta specs with ADDED/MODIFIED/REMOVED requirements, `openspec validate --strict`, `openspec status`/`openspec instructions apply`)
   - CodeMirror 6 (CM6) `EditorState.transactionFilter` as the enforcement choke point; `Transaction.userEvent`, `Transaction.addToHistory`, `StateEffect`, `ChangeSet`/`ChangeSpec`, ChangeSet position mapping
   - CM6's `@codemirror/commands` `history.ts` internals: `HistEvent` with `startSelection`/`selectionsAfter` fields; undo restores `event.startSelection` (pre-edit selection) and pushes a new "undone" event whose `startSelection` is the selection active "at the moment undo runs"; redo restores THAT captured selection directly (no remapping)
   - The outline block-tree model (`OutlineDoc`/`OutlineNode`, `src/model.ts`): nodes own their lines verbatim; blank-line "gaps" are owned by the preceding node (`trailingGap`); `preamble` for frontmatter
   - Pure/impure layering discipline: pure core modules (`ops.ts`, `enforce.ts`, `classify.ts`, `escalate.ts`, `parse.ts`, `encode.ts`, `reencode.ts`, `rules.ts`, `result.ts`) have NO CodeMirror/Obsidian imports; only `src/plugin/*` adapts to CM6/Obsidian
   - Transaction classification taxonomy (6 classes: programmatic, composition, plugin-own, selection-only, within-node-edit, boundary-crossing-edit) — default-permit at the taxonomy level, narrow default-deny only inside boundary-crossing-edit
   - Verdict layer: `pass | rewrite | veto` computed purely from `(class, doc, EditFact)`
   - "Chrome transparency" principle (D9): gap lines and list markers are markdown-encoding-layer chrome; editing semantics must never depend on gap width/ownership or marker internals; recognition of edit INTENT must come from the pre-edit cursor position (`cursorBefore`), not just the raw edit shape, since chrome-crossing edits can be byte-identical to deliberate-chrome edits
   - Content-adjacent merge (D10) and split (D11): merges/splits computed relative to CONTENT boundaries, not raw character positions
   - Marker-transparent cursor placement (D13): `clampCursorToContent` redirects any cursor-only selection landing inside a list item's marker prefix to content-start, scoped ONLY to list markers (not gap lines, not headings)
   - `reindentSubtreeVerbatim` / `reencodeBlocksForDestination` (D15/D16): re-indenting a copied/pasted subtree by swapping the top node's OWN leading-whitespace PREFIX for the destination's indent text (string-prefix swap), preserving descendants' relative indent strings verbatim — avoids `shiftSubtree`'s flat-numeric-column-delta approach which mismatches indent units (tabs vs. spaces) at depth
   - `isStructuralBlockSequence`: shared predicate (more than one top-level block, OR one block with children) used by BOTH `classify.ts` (to decide if a transaction should even reach the verdict layer) and `enforce.ts` (to decide if a paste needs structural splicing) — a recurring bug pattern in this session was "two call sites for one rule, only one kept current"
   - `deleteSubtrees`/`mergeNodes`/`insertSubtrees` are OPS whose output (`OpOutput.doc`) always comes from a FRESH `parse()` reparse inside `finalize()` — meaning node IDs from the pre-reparse "surgery" tree never match IDs in the returned `.doc`. This caused multiple real bugs when code tried to look up nodes by their OLD id in the NEW doc; the fix pattern established is to look up by LINE POSITION (via `nodeAtLine`) instead, or to only ever reference `finalize`'s own pre-computed cursor.
   - Vitest unit/property testing (fast-check `fc.assert`/`fc.property`), `tests/generators.ts`'s `arbTree()` generator
   - WebdriverIO/`wdio-obsidian-service` e2e testing against a REAL (sandboxed) Obsidian instance; `browser.keys()`, `mouseDragSelect`, `dispatchSelectOnlyRanges`, `pasteText`, `h.getStats()`/`h.getCursor()`/`h.getSelection()`/`h.getBuffer()` helpers
   - Known e2e flakiness categories already documented in the codebase: real-mouse-drag timing (`mouseDragSelect`), and (newly observed) nested-table-cell click interactability — both environmental, not code regressions
   - Mobile emulation testing (`OBSIDIAN_E2E_MOBILE=1`, `wdio.mobile-emulation.conf.mts`) — `IS_MOBILE_RUN` guards skip real-pointer-based tests
   - Memory system: persistent memory files at `/Users/laughedelic/.claude/projects/-Users-laughedelic-Code-obsidian-true-outliner/memory/`, indexed via `MEMORY.md`; created `chrome-transparency-editing.md` as a feedback-type memory this session

3. Files and Code Sections:

   - **`src/ops.ts`** (core pure structural operations)
     - Added `deleteSubtrees(doc, nodeIds)`, `mergeNodes(doc, firstId)`, `insertSubtrees(doc, anchorId, parsedBlocks, position)` as the three new Phase C ops.
     - `finalize()` made to accept `subjectId: number | undefined` and exported.
     - `destinationIndent` and `contentColumnCh` exported (were private).
     - `mergeNodes` was REWRITTEN multiple times: first version (single-separator, simple table), then D10 rewrite (cross-kind joins, children re-parenting via `childBaseCol`/`shiftSubtree`, single-line heading absorption), then D12 fix (cursor at join point):
       ```ts
       const result = finalize(doc, surgery, merged.id);
       if (!result.ok) return result;
       const joinLineOffset = first.kind === 'heading' && first.setext ? 0 : first.lines.length - 1;
       const joinLine = result.value.cursor.line + joinLineOffset;
       const joinCh = (first.lines[joinLineOffset] ?? '').length;
       return accept({ ...result.value, cursor: { line: joinLine, ch: joinCh } });
       ```
     - `splitNode` rewritten (D11) so a node WITH children places the split remainder as the new FIRST CHILD.
     - Most recent addition — `reindentSubtreeVerbatim` (exported) and `reencodeBlocksForDestination` (exported, new shared function extracted from `insertSubtrees`):
       ```ts
       export function reindentSubtreeVerbatim(node: OutlineNode, indentText: string): OutlineNode {
         const topWs = leadingWhitespace(node.lines[0] ?? '');
         const swapLine = (line: string): string => {
           if (line.trim() === '') return line;
           const ws = leadingWhitespace(line);
           return ws.startsWith(topWs) ? indentText + line.slice(topWs.length) : line;
         };
         const recur = (n: OutlineNode): OutlineNode => ({
           ...n,
           lines: n.lines.map(swapLine),
           children: n.children.map(recur),
         });
         return recur(node);
       }

       export function reencodeBlocksForDestination(
         doc: OutlineDoc,
         parent: OutlineNode | 'root',
         precedingSiblings: readonly OutlineNode[],
         followingSiblings: readonly OutlineNode[],
         parsedBlocks: readonly OutlineNode[],
       ): readonly OutlineNode[] {
         const indentText = destinationIndent(doc, parent, precedingSiblings);
         const newContentKind = encodingKindAtDestination({
           parentKind: parent === 'root' ? 'root' : parent.kind,
           precedingSiblings,
           followingSiblings,
         });
         return parsedBlocks.map((block) => {
           const isContentBlock = block.kind === 'paragraph' || block.kind === 'list-item';
           if (!isContentBlock || newContentKind === block.kind) {
             return reindentSubtreeVerbatim(block, indentText);
           }
           return reencodeForDestination(block, newContentKind, indentText);
         });
       }
       ```
       `insertSubtrees` now calls `reencodeBlocksForDestination(doc, parent, precedingSiblings, followingSiblings, parsedBlocks)` instead of inline mapping logic.

   - **`src/enforce.ts`** (pure verdict layer)
     - Contains `EditFact`, `Verdict`, `computeVerdict`, `recognizeMergeIntent` (D10 rewrite, cursor-derived), `computeMergeVerdict`, `computeDeletionVerdict`, `computePasteVerdict`, `composeTypeOver`, `deleteAndSplice` (shared helper extracted from composeTypeOver), `isEmptyAnchor` (D14), `endOfInsertedRun`, `siblingCoverIds`, `survivorsOf`, `coverIdsOf`.
     - `computePasteVerdict` uses `isStructuralBlockSequence` (imported from classify.ts) instead of `parsedBlocks.length <= 1`.
     - MOST RECENT FIX — `insertAsOnlyChildren` (D16), previously never re-indented at all, now:
       ```ts
       function insertAsOnlyChildren(
         doc: OutlineDoc,
         parentPath: readonly number[],
         parsedBlocks: readonly OutlineNode[],
       ): OpResult<OpOutput> {
         const parent = parentPath.length === 0 ? 'root' : nodeAt(doc, parentPath)!;
         const reencoded = reencodeBlocksForDestination(doc, parent, [], [], parsedBlocks);
         const rebuild = (nodes: readonly OutlineNode[], depth: number): readonly OutlineNode[] => {
           if (depth === parentPath.length) return reencoded;
           const index = parentPath[depth]!;
           return nodes.map((node, i) =>
             i === index ? { ...node, children: rebuild(node.children, depth + 1) } : node,
           );
         };
         const surgery: OutlineDoc = { ...doc, children: rebuild(doc.children, 0) };
         return finalize(doc, surgery, reencoded[0]?.id);
